The official organa which made Roman law were now, as under the Republic, assisted by the unofficial or semi-official activity of the jurisconsults. Some of these teachers were now given public recog· nition aa authoritative sources of law. We are told that Augustus granted the right to certain jurisconsults to respond under imperial authority; and this practice was continued by his successore on the throne. Amongst the earlier of these patented jurisconsults was Masurius Sabinus, of the time of the Emperor Tiberius ¹. The granting of this privilege did not diminish the activity oi the ' unpatented lawyers ², although it doubtless diminished their in· fluence; but it gave the response of its possessor as authoritative a character as though it had prooeeded from the emperor himsew.
